    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What defines a growth stock?</summary>
        <p>A growth stock is a share in a company that is expected to grow its revenues and earnings at an above-average rate compared to the broader market.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Do growth stocks pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>Most growth stocks do not pay dividends. Instead, management reinvests earnings back into the business to fuel further expansion.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Why are growth stocks often expensive?</summary>
        <p>Growth stocks often trade at high Price-to-Earnings (P/E) ratios because investors are willing to pay a premium now for expected future profitability.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the risks of growth stocks?</summary>
        <p>They are highly sensitive to interest rate changes and market sentiment. If a growth company fails to meet high expectations, its stock price can plummet quickly.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How are growth stocks different from value stocks?</summary>
        <p>Value stocks are typically mature companies trading at a discount to their intrinsic value, often paying dividends, whereas growth stocks are expanding rapidly and reinvesting capital.</p>
      </details>
